Valentine Z wrote:I have learned two things about Gandoor's history:

The Great Depression had a minor effect on the Gandoorese economy, with unemployment reaching a high of 13% in 1932. However, due to Stevenson's economic policies, the economy swiftly recovered and Gandoor, along with Sweden, is considered one of the first countries to recover from the Depression.

So this is one of them, the fact that their economy, while it still suffered, was more of a not-too-great Depression for them, in all honesty. All thanks to their main man Stevenson, so that was good that they could avoid it when the entire world (more or less) was crapping their pants.

Petrikov's era as Prime Minister, known by Gandoorese historians as 'The Lost Era', were characterized by the severe curtailing of civil and political freedoms for all and Gandoor, during the time, was sometimes referred to as a authoritarian state. His goal, as stated in a private 1942 speech, was the transformation of Gandoor into an atheistic socialist single-party state ruled by his Revolutionary Socialist Party, which he formed that same year.

Kinda feels like what the Valentians have went through, what with Valentijn gaining more power until there was a split (in a good way) of the world. Of course, Valentine Z by all accounts is still an autocracy, but anyway, going back to Gandoor's stuff. I kinda see it coming, if I am honest? After a recovery state or some sort of a war/depression/recession/bad event affecting them, it's not unusual for a nation to start being authoritarian, though this is not always a bad thing. Sometimes, if lucky enough, the leader in question can still mean well despite being a single-person/single-party state.


AN: Learning about their languages and speech system, as I have read in the overview:

The bulk of Danelagers speak English. It is, apart from them, spoken by hundreds of millions of folk around the world, and as the first language of England it is spoken by 98% of the land's befolking. It is upsprungly an Indo-Europish tongue in the Anglo-Frisian bough of the Germanic family. It was created by the forbinding of Old Anglo-Saxon spoken by the Anglo-Saxons and the Old Norse spoken by the Danish incomers, and it soon took over as the first language of the land.

So I learned that they still speak English, but I can only wonder (and learn more) about whether or not their English is 1:1 with the English that we have OOCly in real-life, or does it have a lot more Anglo-Saxon English / Old English influence with them, less from the French and other Romance languages?

So I read about their religion, specifically on the Sky Mother and Her Worships. This part was the more interesting bit out of the entire thing:

The Winds of Death are, thankfully, not as horrid as their names suggest. Rather, they are often subdued figures, and rarely portrayed in a negative light, reflecting the Ghesite view on death that it holds no morality but rather simply is.

Reminds me of the Underworld and how people (even including fking Disney!) thinks that Hades is an all-around bad guy when on the contrary, he just has a gig of being the middleman, on top of him actually being one of the nicer deities.

Fascinating how this ancient religion is the exception of such a portrayal of death. At least, I hope I am reading and interpreting this correctly regarding the Winds of Death.
